Ric Werme <werme@werme.ne.mediaone.net> wrote:
>One of the most wonderful aspects of MACRO-10 was its macro language.  It
>had loops, string variables, you could process items one character at
>a time (IRPC).  All these are alien concepts to C programmers, and the
>typical Unix assembler is simply woeful.
>
>Microsoft's Z80 assembler had many of the same features (back in those
>days Microsoft had a PDP-10).

Don't forget the package of programs called MICRO.  The programs has MACRO-10
features because they used MACRO-10 as a cross-assembler.

It consisted of a series of macros written in MACRO-10.
It defined the pseudo ops for 8080/8085/Z80, 6502, 6800, etc.
You could run your microprocessor assembly-language program through
the 36-bit MACRO-10, then post-process the listing file to produce
an 8-bit punched paper tape for the target microcomputer.


