My all time favorite -10 macro was originally written by
Bill Gosper, then at MIT-AI, and it solved the Rubik's
Cube puzzle. That is, the input to the compiler was the present
state of the cube and the output of the compiler was
the solution to the particular puzzle. This was, of course,
originally written in MIDAS-10 (MIT's assembler)
and not MACRO, but was quickly transliterated into
MACRO-10 where it worked just fine. The origin of
this was an ongoing competition at MIT-AI for who
could code a given task in fewer instructions. The
original Rubik's Cube solver at MIT-AI was in
LISP (what else?) and then somebody came up
with a very clever little routine that did the essential
rotations in a neat way, and then the whole
program got down to something like 40 instructions.
At that point Gosper went away for a day or so, then
came back announcing had a program which would
solve the puzzle in zero instructions!

My second favorite was the MACRO-10 macro
that compiled the hyphenation dictionary for the TYPESET-10
project. The macro was about six pages long
and the output was a hash-coded dictionary optimized
for fast access of common words, plus a routine that
added words to the dictionary on the fly and another
that would dump the dictionary into an ASCII format.
One neat thing about it was that the add-word and dump
routines weren't hard coded--they depended on the
density of the dictionary and suchlike for their hash
function, so the macro actually "wrote" the code anew
each time after the main dictionary was compiled and
ready for use. The disadvantage to all this was that
the hyphenation dictionary wasn't entirely expandable...
if you added several thousand words you'd have
to recompile for efficiency. But it sure was efficient when
you started.




