Tymshare had a similar procedure for TYMCOM-IX (24-bit) programs and
TYMCOM-X (36-bit) programs.

1) Developer claims product is ready for release.  Provides
   a list of source files with checksums, and list of output files
   with checksums.

2) Program Librarians copy the files from the Development system to
   their computer.  Following the product's installation instructions,
   they recompile everything from scratch.

3) List of output files and checksums is compared with developer's list.
   If there are any descrepencies, go back to step 1.

4) Product is archived to tape, with three identical savesets per tape.
   First set of tapes placed in local tape library.  Duplicate set of
   tapes sent to off-site storage at the other end of the country.

5) Product installed on all production systems.

Nonstandard compilers were allowed, but only if adequately documented, and
if executable binaries for said compiler were included in the source
distribution.  The goal was to be able to recompile the product on
a system with only the standard utilities in the system directories.
