Back when I worked in TOPS-20 engineering we used to patch the running
monitor on a regular basis.

After the repeated "downsizing" of LCG we ended up with one CFS cluster for
TOPS-20 7.0 development, one cluster which we shared with the TOPS-10 guys,
and awesome old KL1026/1042/1322 which was the TOPS-10 SMP system. There
were two KS10 systems but almost nobody used them.

Gidney, Cloyd, and Ronco, all of them 4 meg(!) 2065s were the primary
TOPS-20 systems in the MRO1-2 lab.

Gidney had the Arpanet IMP interface (tops20.dec.com), ran a lot of general
timesharing, and was about one monitor behind Ronco. Cloyd mostly did batch
jobs (monitor builds and other admin stuff). Gidney and Cloyd were pretty
busy during the day, running load averages in the 5-10 range. Ronco ("Now
how much would you pay?") was the main developer's system. We had about four
RP07s, each system had about 4 RP06s, and four HSC50s serving a whole bunch
of RA81s and two RA60s. The systems were ported to a string of TU73s using a
TX02/TX03. It was a kick ass cluster... those were the days...

There were only two KL systems for general monitor debugging: Chip and Dale
(actually MRCHIP and MRDALE) were in another CFS cluster with two more
HSC50s and were used for debugging. (These are the same two KLs that you may
have seen at DECUS.)

Chip and Dale were set up for serious standalone development. If you had a
serious patch you could be careful and put it into Chip or Dale, but if
someone had them signed up for standalone you would just have to (carefully)
patch Ronco. (Screwing around on Ronco was also good for keeping the load on
Gidney and Cloyd, as they had the reputation for being somewhat more
stable.)

Patching the running monitor was easy and fun, thanks to FILDDT... escape-<
to start a patch, escape -> to finish it.. when you finished it, DDT would
plug in the JRSTs for you. I'd run PHOTO first so I'd have a record of what
I patched (if the system stayed up).

If you blew it, you crashed the monitor and you had a dump to look at. If
you did it right and the system stayed up, you got a thrill, a patch all
ready for MONITR.EXE,  and the "C" part of an SDC file.

Of course patching the running monitor was always great for pranks on other
folks. Example: change a certain manager's username from DBROWN to *BDROWN*
and watch the fun after the connected path was set to ps:<*bdrown*>.

Fake ^ESENDs were also a blast, but that's another story.




