<jmfbahciv@aol.com> wrote in message
news:7us3nm$8on$3@autumn.news.rcn.net...
> <snip>
> I don't see how PIP could mess up batch files.  By the time
> there was a batch, Pete Conklin had started his coding
> standard, I think.  John?  When did that memo come out
> that talked about using symbols instead of number for AC
> assignments, etc.

Easy. Lots of things would break batch files if you weren't careful. Oh, and
I suppose there
can be some confusion about the term "batch" came to mean files that were
executed from a terminal pseudo-thing (PTY).

The primary ways of breakage were:

1)    Commands which were changed to do something differently, and wrong,
    (i.e. inconsistent with documentation) without giving error messages.
This
    was the killer, because the user generally wouldn't even know anything
was
    wrong but the output wouldn't be what was expected. For example, if a
copy
    command was supposed to format the output file in a certain way (and PIP
had
    many of these switches) but didn't, and another program read the output
file
    and checked for a certain string, then it could fail to work but appear
to. This
    made for wrong and inconsistent answers, which is less than desirable
for
    supposedly deterministic machines.

2)    Commands which didn't used to give an error message, but now did.
    This wasn't quite as bad, because at least if you read the log you could
    see something went wrong. Still, it wasn't great. And oftimes people
    wouldn't read the logs of programs that had worked reliably for
    years.

3)    Commands which did something differently than the documentation,
    and were corrected to conform to the documentation in the latest
    release. This is almost as bad as (1) but not quite, and particularly
nasty
    if the command is used as part of an automated process. Again, if the
next
    program searches for a particular string in the output file to check
whether
    the input data meet some condition, then one might never know that the
    programs had changed behavior.

I don't remember all the various switches for PIP, but there were quite a
few
and they could be used in odd combinations. PIP would also do various things
differently on different devices (device independence was as mythological as
the 40 hour work week at DEC LCG). One never knew what users relied upon,
so new versions had to work pretty much like old versions with respect to
all three of the above type of errors.

I remember when PTY's were implemented, because I'd come from MIT AI
where ITS had virtual terminals long long before, but I think that there was
card reader batch support well prior to PTY's, wasn't there? I don't
remember what
batch language it used.





