>How about a thread on all the bootleg projects?

I think I've posted here before about one of the more interesting (and 
off-beat) bootleg projects I was involved with. There was a subculture of auto 
racers in the mill, of which I was one. Fred Gould was the head of the modules 
product line, and a drag racer. Ron Boudreau was in PDP-8 engineering and 
built and raced Formula Vees.

At that time (late '60, early '70s) Bosch had just introduced the first 
electronic fuel injection systems. The automotive press was talking about EFI 
as the technology of the future. We figured the auto industry would be needing 
control modules, and who better to build them than DEC?

I was given permission to devote 20% of my time (one day per week) to the EFI 
project. Ron secured a Bosch EFI module from a wrecked VW, and we disassembled 
and analyzed it. Fred assigned one of his engineers to work with us. We deemed 
the Bosch unit to be extremely primitive by DEC module standards, and 
determined we could reproduce the functionality of the module much more 
compactly and much, much cheaper.

At that time DEC had a relationship with GM by virtue of the PDP-14 project. 
Fred arranged a meeting with some folks at the Hydramatic Division (at that 
time sort of the "R&D" arm of GM) to talk about DECs possible future 
involvement in the production of control modules. Unfortunately the Hydamatic 
folks insisted that there were years of life in carburetors, and when GM 
eventually went to EFI they would probably tool up to produce their own 
control modules. We dropped the "project".

In retrospect, the GM people were dead on. Things happened just the way they 
predicted, and I recall some years ago reading that the largest producer of 
digital circuit modules in the world was GM.

