Was this a TOPS-10 only thing or a general thing?  This usage is familiar,
in the MTS operating system (for IBM mainframes), "Snarked" is the state
that a job is put into when it encounters some impossible condition (at
least I *think* that's what it is).  Typically happens when you've been
playing around with trying to call undocumented low core entry points,
there are all kinds of goodies down there but they don't handle things very
graciously when called by an unpriv'ed program.  So of course the danger
was that the operators would catch on to who's been disasembling low core
(which was forbidden in spite of MTS's grand claims about security) when
they kept finding snarked jobs lying around, all with the same userID...

