On 13 Mar 2000, Peter da Silva wrote:
> Language changes, and we have to adapt. It's been 10 years since I've felt free
> to refer to myself as a "UNIX Hacker" or a "Forth Hacker" unless I was sure the
> folks I was talking to were in the know...

10 years?  It's been about 20 years for me, although I didn't throw in the
towel until the late 1980s.

I remember being interviewed by a reporter for a major Bay Area newspaper
(one that is supposedly tech-savvy) about hackers.  I discovered, to my
horror, that what she wanted to hear was stories about breaking into
systems.  She was completely disinterested in hearing about what, at the
time, we called "hacking" (today, we say "software engineering" or "tool
building" or some other euphemism).

She kept on trying to turn the conversation to breaking into systems.  
When I finally went out and told her that that was *not* the definition of
"hacking", she said something truly remarkable:

"We have decided what hacking means.  If you don't like it, that's just
too bad."

I asked her if it was OK with her if programmers started using the word
"prostitute" to mean "female journalist."


What eventually resulted was a full-page article in which she didn't use
any of the material from me.  However, a number of guys and gals I know
got suckered into her trap.  She embarassed them by trumpeting high school
escapades from 10 years earlier and making it appear as if this was
contemporary activity.  In several cases, she put words into their mouths
that they never said.

The result was my policy of refusing interviews unless I am paid and can
review what will be put in print associated with my name.  That gets rid
of US journalists, although some foreign journalists have agreed.

-- Mark --

