A general thing, sort of:

People read books they like to read.

People interested in computers are generally interested in logic and like to
read books about it. If you read a book you like to read, then you're
familiar with the words in it.

If people like one book by an author, they like to read other books by that
author.

Carroll wrote his wonderful books of logic problems and also the Snark, in
which he invented many imaginary things and named them. Confusing the bow
with the bowsprit was imaginary and was named "snarked."

People like to be thought clever, and someone is considered clever who
discovers or invents something new and gives it a clever name.

An old name is clever if familiar but appropriately applied to something
new. Something is appropriate if it is familiar. Confused computers were new
at the time, but confusion was quite familiar.

If you've followed all this, then it's obvious that computer people at the
time would like to name confused computers "snarked"

Therefore, I'd say that the use by TOPS-10 people was only one instance of
the more general proposition, similarly the usage for MTS.


