In article <MMVA4.6585$Of2.228148@typhoon.ne.mediaone.net>,
Ric Werme  <werme@nospam.mediaone.net> wrote:
: ...
: Perhaps this is a good time to rhetorically wonder why the people who
: think Unix is so broken or Tops-20 was so wonderful have never manage
: to come up with a successful Unix shell that looks like Tops-20.
: Ditto VMS. (Actually, that's been accomplished a couple times, but
: it's never attracted Unix users.)
: 
For those who still use keyboards and (non-curses-menu) text mode, the
COMND JSYS is still -- with certain extensions -- about the best you can
do.  Although the TOPS-20 EXEC had lots of aggravating limitations (many of
which were addressed by local hacks at CMU, MIT, Stanford, etc, and us at
Columbia: multiforking, kept editors, script programming (remember PCL?),
etc), it always had one big advantage over the UNIX shell, namely that it
didn't parse your commands blindly: it knew what field was supposed to be
-- a number, a filename, etc, and so (a) could give you specific help for
it, and (b) could validate it.  The shell, on the other hand, simply fills
in argv, assuming that every token on the command line is a filename, and
every metacharacter is to be used for filename matching.  You don't find
out until after you've entered the whole command what you did wrong, and
you can't find out what comes next if you don't know.

As you probably know, we (at Columbia) wrote a fairly complete COMND
package in C, called CCMD, which is still available:

  ftp://kermit.columbia.edu/ccmd/

A sample program built with it is a UNIX version of the TOPS-20 REV
program, found in the same directory.  Various people have started writing
UNIX shells based on CCMD but I'm not aware of any that were finished
enough to use.

Also C-Kermit, which doesn't actually use CCMD, has pretty much the same
user interface:

  http://www.columbia.edu/kermit/ckermit.html

and has so much file management, etc, built into it that it *almost* can be
a shell.  The main thing lacking any more is job control (but then the Exec
didn't have that either :-).  Plus it adds programmability and intrinsic
directory-tree recursion when building or showing file lists (e.g. when you
type "?" in a filename or directory-name field).  Which, by the way, is not
an easy thing to accomplish in UNIX, which to this day does not have an
API (at least not a widely used one) for getting file lists -- something
that even CP/M 2.2 and DOS 1.0 had.

The different approaches of the EXEC and the UNIX shell tended to require
that the EXEC have all common operations built in, so it could
intelligently parse all fields of all commands.  Whereas the shell just
runs external programs, and you can't get command-line help for any of
them.  VMS sort of tries to find a compromise, but they didn't take it far
enough -- if you type a command incompletely, you are prompted for the next
field, and it doesn't matter whether the command is built in to DCL or is
external -- VMS almost succeeds in hiding the difference from you.  If they
had only taken it one step further and enabled single-character wakeup in
the command parser, with ?-help, completion, etc, it wouldn't have been
half bad.

Oh yeah, and one more thing -- after almost 20 years of using UNIX (after
more than 10 of using PDP-10 and 11 OS's), I still find the one thing I
miss most in UNIX is logical names.  At any large Unix installation like
ours, files are constantly being moved around, and once they move you can
never find them.  This is true for both users and programmers (e.g. where
is ioctl.h; where is [n]curses.h?).  Millions of programs are full of
stupid #ifdefs to find their header files, thousands of makefiles have
paths hardwired into them, and users constantly have to be editing their
PATHs to track slippery applications.  Fooey!

- Frank


