Hey all.

I just lurk here. Mainly because my software involvement with the
10s was restricted to repeatedly crashing ADP's London based
development system (#18), during my brief and ill advised stint
as a programmer there. So 90% of what goes on here is waaay over
my head, but I do recognise a lot of the names. The majority of
my 5 years at ADPNS was as an operator, and later front line
customer support. Despite the unsocial working hours and a shift
pattern that left everyone perpetually tired, I still look back
on my days at ADP with much fondness. The company tended to suck
(of course), but that was more than made up for by the truly
wonderful people I was privileged to work with. Andy, Dave, Tony,
Sal and the rest, you know who you are :) It felt like family,
something I've haven't felt at any other place I've worked.

I don't know how many people here actually worked for ADP, and
how many of those actually saw the London based mainframe room,
but for the curious, I have a photo I took in the early '80s.
Unfortunately you can't see the CPUs (4 triple CPU systems
numbered #15 thru #18) as they are way down the back of the room.
However you can see the LA120 consoles, the tape decks, the
DECTapes and the usual computer room clutter. Of interest is a
set of 4 lights mounted on the ceiling, and numbered (big
surprise) 15-16-17-18. These were linked to their respective
systems in such a way, that in the event of a systems crash, an
air raid siren (really!) would go off and the appropriate light
would turn on. A few seconds before the siren went of, the
consoles would spit out their diagnostics, along with a bunch of
BELLs. Those of us tuned into the sounds of the room (much like a
ship's engineer) were already halfway down the room to reboot the
system before the BELLs and siren had a chance to go off, because
we knew the sound an LA120 makes when printing out the errors.

Although I would never go back to working a regular 12 hour shift
(11:00 - 23:00 days, 23:00-11:00 nights) or frequent 24 hour
stints and occasional 36 hour marathons (like the time the local
substation blew up) I still get the fuzzies when ADPNS is
mentioned.

If anyone is interested in a scan of my photo, I'd be only too
happy to mail them a copy for their web pages.


