On Thu, 23 Mar 2000, Brian Chase wrote:
> Is it immediately inuitive for new users under TOPS-10 how to reattach 
> to detached sessions?  Maybe(?)  But I'd imagine TOPS-10 users would have
> to learn about that mechanism just as Unix users learn about screen.

On TOPS-20, if you tried to log in when you had a detached session, it
would ask you if you wanted to attach back to the detached session instead
of logging in a new job.

One thing that is missed is that the detach was not a "save of state".  
No state is saved, because the only thing being destroyed on a disconnect
is the binding between job and controlling terminal.  The job is still
there, and you can attach back to it at any time.

If you are not logged in, attach requires the password.  If you're logged
in to the same user name as the detached job, then attach just does it
without requiring a password (and detaches the former job).

This latter feature (of being able to rotate between detached jobs) was
used more on TOPS-10 than TOPS-20, because TOPS-20 had multiple processes.  
Attaching/detaching on TOPS-20 was generally used only to recover from a
disconnect or possibly for a "suspend" type situation (you're walking away
from the terminal and want to keep your job safe from prying fingers...).

-- Mark --

