>The shuffler shuffles the monitor code?????  I'm beginning to
>understand why JMF got so down in the dumps when he did the
>Alpha.

I don't know that I'd go so far as saying that it shuffles the monitor
code, but I did have lots of fun battling the MACRO32 compiler and the
hardware on a number of my device drivers. The most annoying bits were:

  - The hardware would re-order and gather writes. Of course, this is
    what the barrier instructions are there to control.
  - The MACRO32 compiler would re-order reads. Fortunately, it didn't
    re-order them across a barrier, so it was still possible to control
    this using barriers.
  - Occasionally, the MACRO32 compiler would optimize out a CSR access.
    The example that springs to mind is a TSTL that I used to clear a
    CSR flag. Since it wasn't followed by a conditional branch, the
    compiler decided the TSTL wasn't needed and tossed it.

Of course, directly mapping CSRs and talking to them was not the official
way to do things under VMS (it still isn't, although there are now some
decent alternatives to the CRAM stuff for systems that _can_ talk directly
to the CSRs). My device driver style tends to be of the "bonk VMS over
the head and steal its wallet variety"; I was porting a VAX TURBOchannel
driver to the Alpha and didn't want to rewrite it, so I just mapped the
CSRs on the Alpha as I had on the VAX (did I mention that I had a couple
of VAX TURBOchannel drivers running before DEC had TURBOchannel support
ready? I kind of _had_ to bonk VMS over the head and steal its wallet).
