In article <qhd7ocov10.fsf@ruckus.brouhaha.com> Eric Smith
<eric-no-spam-for-me@brouhaha.com> writes:

> I don't know if TOPS-20 did it the way I'm about to propose, but it seems
> like the "correct" behavior with a versioning filesystem would be somewhere
> inbetween the TOPS-10 and Unix approaches.

> When you open an existing file for write (overwrite from beginning, not
> random-access update), it should create a new file with an incremented
> version number.  Programs with the older version open should continue to use
> that.  Programs that open the file in the default way (without specifying a
> version) after the new version is created but before it is closed should get
> the old version.  Programs that want to access the new version while it's
> being written (e.g., "tail -f") should be able to explicity specify the
> version number, or perhaps specify an open option meaning "absolute latest
> version".

;-> You've been reading the _Tops-20 Monitor Calls Reference Manual_, haven't
you?  That's a *very* good description of the way file generations work on
Tops-20.

> The policy decision as to whether to delete the old version once all channels
> to it have been closed can be left to the system manager or end user.

It is left to the individual user; the standard system default is to keep only
1 generation of each file, though I suppose someone with sources could change
that number.  There are actually two such settings:  The directory may have a
particular default assigned to it, and a group of files can have a different
setting than the directory default.

Another nice feature of the Tops-20 filesystem is that deleting a file is
really a two-step process:  The DELETE command in the EXEC (a call of the DELF%
JSYS) only marks a file as deleted in the FDB; the space is not reclaimed until
someone executes a call of the DELDF% JSYS (via an explicit EXPUNGE command in
the EXEC or an implicit expunge by logging out).  Of course, user programs can
use those JSYi as well--MMailr, the MTA portion of the MM mail system, handles
its queue directory by explicit calls of DELF% and DELDF%, since it normally
runs as a daemon and never logs out.

The point of that little side-trip is that if the user creates one or more
new generations of a file, and then realizes that an old one should be kept,
a simple UNDELETE will recover one or all deleted generations--and then a new
generation retention can be set for them.  Cuts way down on the number of
requests for file restoration from backups.

