Patrick Scheible wrote:

> The command processor was the exec, which could be replaced without
> changing the monitor.  I'm not sure if a skilled user could replace
> his exec alone, ...

There's a reference to a TREPLACE command in Alice's PDP-10:

"
After the ordeal, Ann took us back downstairs and left us with the CLU
hackers.  She said "Kid, I'm gonna leave you with the CLU hackers.  I
want your jsys manual and your ROLM DTI".  I said "Ann, I can
understand your wanting my jsys manual so I won't remind the CLU
hackers of grody things like operating systems, but what do you want
my DTI for?" and she said "Kid, we don't want any VTS errors".  I said
"Ann, did you think I was going to try to crash the system for
littering?"  Ann said that she was making sure, and friends, Ann was,
'cause she cleared all my left-hand privs bits so I couldn't logout.
And she disabled the TREPLACE command so I couldn't crock in an
XCT [0] instruction, cause an illegal instruction interrupt to MEXEC,
and sneak into MDDT.  Yeah, Ann was making sure, and it was about four
or five hours later that Chiappa (remember Chiappa?  This song's never
even mentioned Chiappa) Chiappa came by and with a few gratuitous
insults to the CLU hackers bailed us out of there, and we went out and
had another Chinese dinner that couldn't be beat, and didn't get up
until the next morning when we all had to go to LCS Computational
Resources staff meeting.
"

Recollection:

TREPLACE was the way to replace the top-level exec - it's not as if
there was a per-user exec preference, at least not initially.

I don't know about *that* TREPLACE, but I think the one I recall only
worked for wheels - it would select fork 0 (the user's top-level EXEC
itself), and use DEPOSIT to patch in code to run the preferred exec.

I might have used it before the multi-forking EXEC (and later PCL) was
party-approved in MR.



>... or if system administrators would have to install it
> for everyone.  There weren't as many execs as there are shells, or (as
> far as I know) such large differences between them.  I can guess at
> several reasons: smaller user community, the standard exec was better
> to start with than sh or csh, the disk space was expensive enough that
> one would have trouble justifying it just to customize execs,
> restricted source code access after the 70s.

One guy in the GALAXY group started using a wildly different program
as his EXEC.  I'm tempted to say it was MACLISP.  I think several other
programs like ITS EMACS would have been plausible top-level EXECs on
TOPS-20.
				/AHM
