Tim Shoppa  <shoppa@trailing-edge.com> wrote:
>I'm not sure I've heard it called the "write protect ring", I
>always hear it called the "write ring".  I'll have to dig

Ditto.  You put a write ring in so you can write to it.  When you finish
writing to it you pull the ring out.  (We'd got this to the point of
reflex -- when you dismounted a reel you were expected to immediately
remove the write ring and toss it into the big box of discarded write
rings.  Tapes got write rings either because they already ad 'em out
of the box (in which case they were emty anyway) or when a positive 
decision to scratch a tape was made.

It meant that if you werent on the ball it was likely that you'd try
to mount a tape for writing without the write-ring in, but you had 
to be having a really bad day to get it wrong the other way.

The dreaded TU58 (and presumably other tapes in the same or similar form
factors) had a slider to write enable or protect the media.  If you
wanted to really protect it you could remove the slider completely.  You
can do the same with 3.5" disks, but it tends to require weapons to do...

-- don


