Bill Westfield wrote:

> As I recall, "operators" did things like mount user tapes, burst and
> distribute printouts, swap tapes for backups, process user backup restore
> requests, burst printouts, reload the lineprinter with paper, and show the
> MBA students where the power switch on the decwriter was.  Somehow none of
> those seem immensly likely to be performed adequately by a "well designed
> operating system."

Back when I was doing this during my college years, the biggest single thing I

did was read in cards :-)  Most of the time I was saved from having to burst
printouts as there were I/O clerks for that.  Swapping disk packs was
another biggy.  In addition to working part time at college I had a summer
job a couple summers at a large well known firm.  Like the walls of tape
drives which preceded it, they had walls of IBM 2314's.  I was quickly
taught how to change packs.  You turned off the power, waited about a
second or so, ripped the drawer open and then put the palms of both
hands down on the top of the still rapidly spinning pack to brake it even
faster than the loudly clicking drive brake could (but not so fast as to
burn your hands although I came close a couple of times ;-)  This seemed
to be SOP at this commercial site.  The IBM CE's were aware of it.
If I had done this at the college computer center they'd have thrown me
off the roof of the computer center ;-) (and I would have helped them,
but when in Rome...)  I think the programmers at this site were having
trouble thinking beyond tapes as they called for disk changes on the
new systems then being installed about as fast as tape changes on
the older systems.

> A poorly designed operating system might keep operators busy doing
> additional pointless stuff, and a well designed operating system gave the
> operators enough free time between tasks to hack or play or read, but
> "unattended" wasn't a realistic choice...

The biggest thing I found I could do was help with the "scheduling".
Usually a batch system will stop and wait for a resource, thus idling
the "expensive" machine and slowing the throughput.  Instead of
just reading in the cards as they came I would "batch" jobs which
had similar requirements for tapes or disks.  If a job required
several tapes I would mount them before reading in the job, then
read in the job and up its priority so it would be the next one run.
Thus the machine didn't have to wait for me to mount tapes or
disks.

Chris
