don@news.daedalus.co.nz (Don Stokes) writes:

>You do of course need a powerfail interrupt and enough time between
>detecting loss of mains power and loss of DC power out of the PSUs to 
>quickly squirrel away enough state in memory to recover (since 
>loss of power to the CPU will cause loss of the CPU's state, registers
>etc), but if your PSUs are any good they have a bit of last gasp 
>power to cover minor fluctuations anyway.

Different manufacturers had different ideas about what was appropriate
protection against power fluctuations.  At my PPOE at one time we had 
an S/360-65, S/370-148, and a DEC KL-10, and (partly at my urging) had
bought a Dranitz power line monitor.  Based on matching the printout
of power-line incidents from the Dranitz to system failures, we found
that the -148 (which had an MG set) could survive nearly a full second
of interruption to the power; the -65 (no MG) would hold up for about
16 cycles, and the KL-10 never survived more than about 5 cycles
of outage.  (The campus power was -- to put it charitably -- not
particularly reliable or clean.)

Joe Morris


