When the IBM PC was announced, the Director of the Division of Computer
Research and Technology (DCRT) at the National Institutes of Health
personally saw to it that about 20 (exact number missing from memory) were
ordered and spread around the division just to see what they might be
useful for. Why? Well, we were, and still are, a moderately large
administrative IBM mainframe shop, so the prevailing opinion was that if
IBM made it, it had to be worth something. Even though us techie types kept
saying to ourselves "why in the world did they do it THAT way", before long
IBM PCs were sitting on every desk.

We also provided timesharing to the general scientific community with a
3-processor DECsystem-10. When the 36-bit line was tossed down the tube, it
sure wasn't a VAX system that replaced it: the Un*x guys had been waiting
for their chance, and this was it. Granted, the "replacement" was a
top-of-the-line Convex system (with DECnet, no less), but the camel's head
was in the tent even though several of the most popular TOPS-10
applications were never ported nor were they even replaced with
semi-equivalents. Cold turkey, it was - after all, everyone just knew that
Un*x was going to completely take over the world in a year or two......(the
Convex was swapped for an SGI multiprocessor system a few years ago). The
IBM is still there, and there are still several dozen VMS systems chugging
away in niches here and there, too.

