Huge rambling follows, please read fully as to avoid any hostility :)

***

All the below is said with a sarcastic grin and a good sense of humor.
I don't mean to offend anyone, I'm just playing devil's advocate.

Mark Crispin wrote:
>
> > The -20 did some stuff better than the -10.
>               ^^^^ most
> > I would have rather written user mode programs using the -20
> > monitor calls interface for one thing.

I found the TOPS-20 operating system to be much better organized than
TOPS-10. A by-product of re-writing an operating system from scratch
for a system that had been around a little while. Of course, the people
involved probably INTENDED this to happen. I liked it a lot, but for
some reason, I couldn't accept it in the face of TOPS-10. Why not
continue refining and redefining tops-10? All of TOPS-20 could have
been done inside the framework of TOPS-10.
 
> Here are some more:
> 
> TOPS-20 had forks, TOPS-10 did not.

Yes, it did. The only problem was you had to use a PTY, log it in, and
then deal with the I/O associated with it. If you used a sharable high-seg,
the forked job would get a complete SHARED copy of the memory of the 
parent. The low-seg would be used to keep private stuff. A careful
programmer could do wonders... I'll admit, the overhead in doing
so was higher than in TOPS-20, but hey... bear with me :)

> TOPS-20 had a shell, TOPS-10 had the command processor built into the
>  kernel (this is a consequence of not having forks).

I found this to be an advantage in half the cases. The other half, of
course, by default, having a shell improved things, but I can still
think of quite a few problems I've had where the command shell being
part of the monitor would have helped.

The biggest advantage of an in-kernel (monitor) command parser was
the ^C, CCONT sequence. Run something, hit ^C and type CCONTI (CCONTINUE)
or just plain CC and be able to do other things while the job was
running (like DETach). UNIX has it with ^Z (stop), but I liked
to be able to E and D the memory of a program I was running.

> TOPS-20 had long file names, TOPS-10 had 6.3 (worse than DOS!).

Hey, if you can't remember that "MMWCB.DAT" didn't equate to
"My Mother Wears Combat Boots.dat" (typical Windows 95 file name),
I can't help you there. :) 

Besides, with some engineering, TOPS-10 UFD's could easily cover
much longer filenames and be compatible with previous versions.

> TOPS-20 had user names, TOPS-20 had a pair of octal numbers

Again, there was a mapping to a username, but it wasn't obvious. 
I kinda liked it. One 36-bit word was better than 2 or 3 words for
a username in ASCII (or SIXBIT).

> TOPS-20 had file/memory mapping, TOPS-10 did not.

You're right, and it was one of the biggest leaps I had made when working
with VAX-11/780's. You could map an entire database file into memory and
then work on it like memory. Too bad it was so slow that I could have
made my own cache and buffering structure and used my own routines and
greatly improved performance. But, my boss and I had made the design
decision to go ahead with mapping... oh well... another problem was
the customer was reluctant to add more physical memory, since it was
costly. 

> TOPS-20 had the debugger always available, in TOPS-10 you had to link
>  the program with the debugger.

Not a big deal for me, UNIX these days still requires you to compile with
an extra switch to keep symbol information. Without it, it's still possible
to debug the program, remember DDT? I used it quite a lot to hack hack hack.
Not to mention E and D (examine and deposit) and "start <address>".

Hmm... in looking over the previous paragraph I realize that I never actually
had to link the debugger into the program to be debugged. Is the above true
about having to link in the debugger? I seem to remember that it was not 
required.

> TOPS-20 had user mode extended addressing, I don't think that TOPS-10
>  ever did.

I kinda think the KL10 could do this. I seem to remember playing around with
this on KS10's. I could access quite a bit more memory than would be normal 

I used it to generate large matrixes representing something -
DAMN, but I don't remember. I had to hand-code some things, since
the MACRO-10 compiler didn't deal with the extensions available on the
KS10. If I just dumped OCTAL code into memory and ran it, I could
do much more in terms of large-scale memory, but I don't remember how
I did it... In this time, I had access to the microcode for the KS10
and that may have had something to do with it, but honestly I don't
remember.

> TOPS-20 had the COMND% JSYS, TOPS-10 had (shudder) SCAN/WILD.
> TOPS-20 had command and filename completion, TOPS-10 did not.

Sorry, but if I can type the first few chars of a command, why hit
<ESC> to complete it, for verbosity? Or for the beep that said you
hadn't typed enough characters yet?

As for filename completion, I've been bitten too many times by that
sort of thing...

Yeah, SCAN/WILD could have used some help, but with TOPS-20 experience,
could you go back and implement it under TOPS-10?

> The most ruinous limitation of TOPS-10 was the lack of forks, which made
> TOPS-10 quite obsolete by the mid-1970s.

Again, you just had to be creative. Dump your entire range of volatile
memory to a file (context switch), launch another job (PTY) and let it get 
it from there. Or use shareable highsegs - my favorite. Multi-threaded
(jobs) stuff is quite easy when they each have access to the same memory.
Matter of fact, I can think of a few different ways to do POSIX threads with
TOPS-10, albeit emulated.

> There were a few things that TOPS-10 did better (e.g. SMP) but that wasn't
> enough to prevent VMS from taking over.

Not priveleged enough to ever experience it, although I had hacked into a
PDP-10 with two CPU's in the late 70's. Pretty strong machine, I don't
remember what class (KA,KI,KL). I believe KL.

From what I saw as an outside customer (way outside), DEC was whole-hog
into the 32-bit VAX while the K line was (to me) the way to go. Imagine
a 72-bit KX10 based on Alpha technology? I just got a warm feeling in
my gut :) I know a few hardware designers that could produce this sort
of thing in a Xilinx chip. Should I figure out what it would take to
produce a PDP-10 on a chip based on Timothy Stark's code?

***

All the above is said with a sarcastic grin and a good sense of humor.
I don't mean to offend anyone, I'm just playing devil's advocate.

***

The main dichotomy in the above results from people comparing static versions
of TOPS-10 with TOPS-20. Given the larger systems that TOPS-20 ran on,
could TOPS-10 have been expanded to include the functionality of TOPS-20
without losing the "feel"?

by the way, what IS the statute of limitations on hacking?

-- 
