Intriguing, though I can't find exactly that.


30 was the crash word - poke it nonzero for a crash:

XPP CRSHWD,30		;NORMALLY THIS WORD WILL BE 0.  IF IT IS ACCIDENTALLY
			; OR PURPOSEFULLY OVERWRITTEN THE MONITOR WILL
			; ATTEMPT TO SAVE THE AC'S AND THE STATE OF
			; ALL DEVICES, THEN HALT.   [A LA 407 RESTART]

See http://pdp-10.trailing-edge.com/pdp-10/TOPS10_704_MONITORANF_BB-X140C-SB/S.MAC
for other cool low locations.


However, I see every CPU had once-a-jiffie and once-a-second dispatch
variables (COMMON.MAC):

CWRD (STO,SC'N'TIC##)		;;SCANNER ONCE A TICK ROUTINE FOR THIS CPU
CWRD (ISR,SC'N'SEC##)		;;SCANNER ONCE A SECOND

I don't think they were intended to be dynamically user-frobbable,
though a whole lot of devices were serviced periodically from those
routines:

SC'N'TIC::SE1ENT
	TTSTRT(M'N'TTG0,DL0TQ'N,DL0STO)
	TTSTRT(M'N'TTG1,DL1TQ'N,DL1STO)
	TTSTRT(M'N'68L0,CC0TQ'N,CC0STO)
...
SC'N'SEC::SE1ENT
	TTSECN(M'N'TTG0,DL0DSP)
	TTSECN(M'N'TTG1,DL1DSP)
	TTSECN(M'N'68L0,CC0DSP)
...


On the other hand, I once wrote a user-mode jiffy interrupt routine
APRENB.  It checked to make sure that the stack pointer hadn't
overflowed with an ``ADD P,[n,,n]'' - unlike PUSHJ, etc., ``ADD P,''
wouldn't cause a PDL overflow trap.

Unfortunately, the idioms

	MOVEM	17,SAVEAC+17	; Free AC17 for later use
	MOVEI	17,SAVEAC	; BLT pointer (AC0,,SAVEAC)
	BLT	17,SAVEAC+16	; Save the rest of the AC's
-and-
	MOVSI	17,SAVEAC	; Get ready to restore the AC's
	BLT	17,17		; Restore AC's 0-17

are tiny windows when P can justifiably not be a legal PDL, and the
code would falsely report PDL overflows if the clock ticked while
BLTting ACs.  It was surprising how quickly that flaw surfaced, but at
least it was a good learning experience.
				/AHM
