by Arthur Krewat <krewat@bartek.net>:
> "Douglas W. Jones,201H MLH,3193350740,3193382879" wrote:

>> ...  Either that, or I have hanging chad on my tape.

> Now, that's damn funny!

It's not a joke.  The particularl photoelectric paper tape reader I have
doesn't have a sprocket to advance the tape, just a pinch roller and
capstan.  The reader reads the sprocket hole in order to clock the data
transfers from the data hole, and hanging chad on the sprocket hole is
rare but more likely than on other holes (the sprocket hole is much
smaller than the data holes, and as a result, wear in the punch die is
likely to lead to hanging chad there before on other holes).

Low speed readers use a sprocket to advance the tape and a mechanical
sensor to find each data hole.  High speed readers with sprockets tend
to poke the hanging chad out of the hole after a few passes, but with
just a pinch roller and capstan, it's quite possible to end up ironing
the chad neatly back into its hole.

