> Tops-10 eventually supported user-accessible multi-forking (up to four per job)
> at release 7.04; the impression I got was that it was not available any earlier
> than that.

The quickest and dirtiest way to do forks/threads was to run everything in
a shareable high-seg and start up "children" by logging in a PTY, running
the program and detaching. IIRC, there were other ways to launch other
jobs, but the easiest (for me, at the time) was to use a PTY and DETACH it.
This was under 6.03 TOPS-10.

This allowed you to run as many threads as you needed. They all communicated
using the shareable high-seg, and kept their private memory in the low-seg.

I employed this method while developing WINDOW - a home-grown networking
daemon. It used to bug the operator when he did a SYSTAT, too many WINDOWs!

