[J_Sauter]
I had a problem like this on the Burroughs B-5000.
The Algol compiler was written in Algol, and so needed 
a working Algol compiler to compile itself.  The 
solution was to code the compiler in a subset of Algol.
When changing the compiler you make very sure that
the subset does not break.  This isn't a very satisfactory
solution, I confess.

Here is an attempt at a better solution.  You start with
a system containing only field-image software.  You
compile and link the new linker on it, and replace the
field-image linker with the new linker.  You then
compile the assembler and all of the compilers used
by the monitor and layered products, link them using
the new linker, and install them on the system.

You then assemble and compile all the rest of the
software that will be in the release, and install it
on the system for testing.  If something turns out
to be broken in the linker, the assembler or a 
compiler, you fix it in source, re-install field-image 
software on your test system, and start the process over 
again.

What do you think?

