Folks, let's be reasonable here.

The problem isn't that MS used DOC for Word files.  Back when that
decision was made, nobody would have thought of reading a Word (or any
other PC application) file on a PDP-10.  Nor for that matter would anyone
have thought of reading a PDP-10 file on a PC.

It was perfectly reasonable for the PC to decide that all DOC files are
Word files, just as on the PDP-10 we decided that all MAC files were
assembly language source code.  We didn't give a damn about the file
naming conventions of other platforms either.  It's actually pretty
remarkable that Microsoft followed *some* of our conventions (e.g. TXT,
EXE).

The thing to bash Microsoft for is that today, in a world in which we have
networking and cross-platform file sharing, that Microsoft hasn't fixed
it; in particular, that Microsoft hasn't moved beyond the "the type of a
file is decided by whatever is after the rightmost period in the file
name."

We're not going to get much sympathy from Microsoft because they made the
same design decisions that we did.  We'll get much further by saying "you
guys claim to be doing the future.  Fine; that means that you have to fix
these extension dependencies."

Those of us who use UNIX can't be too smug either.  Some of these fancy
schmanchy file browsers for UNIX key on the string after the rightmost
period in the file name and change their behavior accordingly.  Even
though you aren't supposed to on UNIX.

Baby programmers can be found on any platform.

-- Mark --

